WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.760
Once your Python project is set up, you're probably eager to start coding. But what do you write?

00:00:06.520 --> 00:00:10.640
Often, the first step will be to download some Python libraries.

00:00:11.240 --> 00:00:13.840
Take the PyTuesday project, for example.

00:00:14.080 --> 00:00:19.639
They've created a handy library that makes grabbing those weekly datasets an absolute breeze.

00:00:19.920 --> 00:00:24.160
So let's show you how to install the PyTuesday library right now.

00:00:25.040 --> 00:00:28.400
First, we'll head over to the terminal tab in positron.

00:00:29.160 --> 00:00:34.200
We'll use Pip, Python's go-to package manager, to handle the installation.

00:00:34.799 --> 00:00:40.040
In the terminal, you'll simply type pip install PyTuesday.

00:00:40.919 --> 00:00:48.360
As soon as you hit enter, Pip gets to work, automatically downloading the library and any other dependencies it needs.

00:00:48.880 --> 00:00:50.000
Think of it like this.

00:00:50.520 --> 00:01:03.799
Just as you download a book from an online store, we're downloading the PyTuesday library from a vast online collection of Python libraries called the Python Package Index, or PyPI.

00:01:05.080 --> 00:01:12.440
If you ever want to see which packages are currently installed in your environment, just type pip freeze in the terminal.

00:01:13.120 --> 00:01:16.800
This command lists every library along with its version number.

00:01:17.320 --> 00:01:28.559
This output is incredibly useful for reproducing your project's environment, which is why you'll often see the output of this command saved to a file called requirements.txt.

00:01:29.440 --> 00:01:35.720
Now that PyTuesday is installed, you are ready to start using its powerful functions in your Python code.

